INSERT INTO `incidents` VALUES
(1,'2018-03-05 08:44:20',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor was found using his chest during One-Handed. When discussing this issue with the delegate, the competitor mentioned he had also done this in previous competitions. There is no video proof available to retroactively identify the attempts in which he broke the Regulations by using his chest.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided to not disqualify any of the prior attempts as it is not possible to track which attempts where affected. Additionally, as none of the past cases were noticed by judges, we believe the competitor did not have a significant advantage by using his chest.','2018-03-31 11:18:50','Competitor used his chest in some OH attempts in previous competitions','2020-05-04 18:08:20'),
(2,'2018-03-05 09:00:47',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: As of 2025, there is now a clear regulation, regulation [3k2b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2b), that states that cubes with a logo during multiblind should count as unsolved. \r\n\r\nA competitor used a cube with a logo in his Multi-Blind attempt. This was only found after the attempt.\r\nCurrently, according to [3k2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2), using a non-permitted puzzle results in DNF of the attempt. As this would be a very harsh consequence in Multi-Blind, the WRC has decided count the non-permitted puzzle as unsolved, without affecting other puzzles\r\nThe WRC is discussing how to revise the Regulations to reflect this policy (see [GitHub issue](https://github.com/thewca/wca-regulations/issues/545)).','2018-03-09 11:00:40','A competitor used one cube with a logo in a Multi-Blind attempt ','2025-06-07 02:19:21'),
(4,'2018-03-31 13:13:48','2018-03-31 13:41:27',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor set a time of 7.51 seconds. When checking the video of the solve, it was clear that the solve took more than 7 seconds. The timer was checked and it was found that the timer would stop for a while after lifting both hands. The timer was removed and an extra attempt was granted by the Delegate.','2018-03-31 13:15:11','Timer ran in slow mode','2018-03-31 13:41:27'),
(5,'2018-03-31 13:40:08','2018-03-31 13:41:36',1,NULL,NULL,'A judge did not use a sight blocker in a succesful solve. An extra attempt was granted just in case, but the Board decided that the original result should stand.\r\n\r\nFor an updated ruling on this type of cases please see this [Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/21).','2018-03-31 13:40:59','3x3x3 Blindfolded solve without sight blocker','2020-05-04 17:58:37'),
(6,'2018-03-31 13:55:07','2018-03-31 13:55:15',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor got a succesful 5x5x5 Blindfolded solve. The result wasn\'t written on the score sheet, but the competitor had recorded the solve, so the time was retrieved from the video and the result accepted as official.','2018-03-31 13:55:11','5x5x5 Blindfolded result missing on the score sheet','2018-03-31 13:55:15'),
(7,'2018-03-31 14:02:21','2018-03-31 14:02:28',1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: As of 2025, logos are now permitted for 3x3 Blindfolded, but not other blindfolded events per regulation [3l](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3l)\r\n\r\nDuring the competition, it was noticed that a lot of competitors were using perceptible logos for Blindfolded events. The competitors were asked to remove such logos.\r\n\r\n','2018-03-31 14:02:25','Perceptible logos for Blindfolded events','2025-06-01 21:21:23'),
(8,'2018-03-31 14:11:51','2018-03-31 14:11:58',1,NULL,NULL,'A mildly colorblind US competitor is trying out special glasses for the colorblind called [EnChroma](http://enchroma.com/) that block out some parts of the color spectrum. It has been decided that these glasses are not likely to offer an unfair advantage, and should be allowed under the current Regulations.','2018-03-31 14:11:55','EnChroma glasses','2018-03-31 14:12:08'),
(9,'2018-03-31 14:26:07','2018-03-31 14:26:20',1,NULL,NULL,'One competitor was found doing their attempts without a Mat, which was not provided by the organization team for the 3x3x3 With Feet event, and it was disqualified from the event. It was decided that the organization team is responsible to provide the competition equipment, and that the competitor should have been granted extra attempts.','2018-03-31 14:26:16','3x3x3 With Feet solving without a Mat','2020-06-18 14:11:39'),
(10,'2018-03-31 14:37:03','2018-03-31 14:37:22',1,NULL,NULL,'Competition scrambles were generated using an old version of TNoodle. The decision was to accept the competition results as official.','2018-03-31 14:37:20','Non-currently-official version of TNoodle used to generate scrambles','2018-03-31 14:37:22'),
(11,'2018-03-31 14:55:07','2018-03-31 14:55:12',1,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER:*  After the resolution of this incident, regulation [4b1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b1) has been changed to explicitely disallow scramble filtering by delegates.\r\n\r\nThere was a very lucky scramble during the 2x2x2 Cube final. A competitor got NR on that scramble, and everyone went to congratulate him. The Delegate changed the scramble group suspecting filtration of the solve. All the solves were kept.','2018-03-31 14:55:10','Scramble filtering','2025-05-21 14:44:44'),
(12,'2018-03-31 14:59:44','2018-03-31 15:04:03',1,NULL,NULL,'One competitor was found to be using a non-official Stackmat timer, which wasn\'t provided by the organization team for the 3x3x3 With Feet event, and it was granted an extra attempt. It was decided that the organization team is responsible to provide the competition equipment, and the result of the extra attempt was accepted.','2018-03-31 15:04:01','3x3x3 With Feet solving with a non-official Stackmat','2018-03-31 15:04:03'),
(13,'2018-04-01 12:56:14','2018-06-08 09:49:55',1,NULL,NULL,'The delegate of [ERAU Speedcubing Spring 2018](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/competitions/ERAUSpeedcubingSpring2018) accidentally used scrambles from a prior competition ([STEM Educ8 2018](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/competitions/STEMEduc82018)) for multiple rounds of this competition. These scrambles have been publicly accesible since the results of the earlier competition were published.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided that all affected results of ERAU Speedcubing Spring 2018 will not be accepted as official WCA results. These are: 2x2x2 Cube, 3x3x3 Cube, 4x4x4 Cube, 3x3x3 One-Handed, Pyraminx and Square-1.\r\nAccordingly, only the results of Megaminx and 7x7x7 Cube will be recognized.\r\n\r\nWe know that this is a harsh decision with consequences for many young competitors. However, the integrity of scrambles in WCA competitions is essential and does not allow us to be lenient here.','2018-04-01 12:58:52','Delegate accidentally reused scrambles from previous competition','2018-06-08 09:49:55'),
(14,'2018-04-04 18:30:18',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'At Kansai Open 2018, 3x3x3 Multi-Blind was held as \"Best of 2\" with a cumulative time limit in combination with the regular time limit. The WCA Guidelines clarify it is not possible to hold 3x3x3 Multi-Blind with a cumulative time limit.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided that all results of the second attempt should be removed. This decision only affected one comeptitor (all other results were DNS).','2018-04-04 18:30:27','Irregular enforcement of time limits for 3x3x3 Multiple Blindfolded','2018-04-04 18:30:27'),
(15,'2018-04-08 18:05:33',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'There were several issues and concerns regarding the venue setup at this competition. The main point was that waiting competitors were able to watch competing competitors. Additionally, it was obviously possible to choose scramble groups by cutting the waiting line.\r\n\r\nThe questionable setup was reported by a competitor who intentionally tried to abuse it by pre-inspecting scrambles in one round. The WRC agreed with him to change all his results from this particular round to DNF.','2018-04-08 18:05:56','Several issues with the venue setup','2018-04-08 18:05:56'),
(16,'2018-04-08 18:14:35',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor reported that he had received the same scrambles for the first and second attempt in Square-1. It turned out that both attempts were scrambled correctly so the result of the second attempt was initially recorded as DNF but an extra attempt was granted.\r\n\r\nAs both cube shapes were indeed similar, the WRC has decided to accept the result of the extra attempt to acknowledge the honesty of the competitor and to avoid discouraging competitors from reporting repeated scrambles.','2018-04-08 18:14:41','Competitor mistakenly reported duplicate scramble in Square-1','2018-04-08 18:14:41'),
(17,'2018-04-16 11:30:28',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor was late for the first round of 4x4x4 and 5x5x5. He asked the organizer if it would still be possible to compete, which  was denied. As the competitor was also a staff member, he decided to ask a fellow staff member to scramble and judge his attempts.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided that the results of both rounds must be removed. The competitor abused his position as a staff member and got a preferential treatment through this. This was also a violation of [4b4](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b4) as the scrambles had already been used earlier.','2018-04-16 11:30:58','Staff member competes in missed rounds without knowledge of Delegate and organizer','2020-05-04 18:02:02'),
(18,'2018-04-16 11:34:19',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since resolution of this incident, regulation [2i2a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i2a) has been updated to allow for delegate discretion for this type of incident.\r\n\r\nA competitor used a front-facing camera in the first round of 2x2x2. This was noticed before the 3rd attempt. He admitted he had used the same camera setup in the previous rounds.\r\nThe WRC decided to DNF the previous results per [2i2a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i2a)\r\n\r\n','2018-04-16 11:35:02','Competitor filmed his attempts with a front-facing camera','2025-05-11 17:07:11'),
(19,'2018-04-16 11:50:36',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'Both the competitor\'s and the judge\'s signatures were found missing for one attempt in Skewb after the competition. The WRC decided to change the result to DNF.\r\n\r\nThis incident is violating and ignoring [A7b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7b) and [A7c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7c). More concrete, the judge did not acknowledge that the result is correct, complete, properly formatted, and clearly readable and the competitor did not check and sign the result. These are the steps to finish an attempt.\r\n\r\nAlthough this can be seen as a harsh decision, we believe that these are important regulations to assure the correctness and validness result. For that reason, accepting results which were done without following [A7b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7b) and [A7c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7c), should not be accepted as valid results.','2018-04-16 11:53:44','Missing signatures found after the competition','2018-05-25 15:19:22'),
(20,'2018-04-17 11:27:26',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'In the final round of Skewb, a competitor received a good result and reacted excitedly. While he was inattentive for a short moment, his judge did not write the result down but sent the puzzle back to the scrambling table. This was discovered when the competitor realized he didn\'t sign for the attempt. A provisional extra attempt was granted at the competition.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided that the original result should be kept. The judge did not follow the approach described in the Regulations. More specifically, he ignored [A7b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7b) by not recording the result. We believe that this should not result in a disadvantage for the competitor. Furthermore, there was enough proof that the original result was legit (recordings as well as eyewitnesses).','2018-04-17 11:27:40','A judge sent the cube back to the scrambling table before the competitor could sign','2020-05-04 18:11:26'),
(21,'2018-04-18 16:45:55',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER*: After these incidents took place, [B4c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/full/#B4c) has been changed to explicitly state that in similar incidents the original solve can stand, if the delegate believes the competitor didn\'t have any bad intentions\r\n\r\nA judge forgot to hold a sheet between the competitor\'s face and the puzzle. This was found after the end of the attempt and a provisional extra was granted.\r\nThe WRC decided to accept the result as there was no sign of the competitor abusing the situation and it was not his fault.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe same situation occurred during PBQ Berkeley 2018 where the original attempt was kept.\r\n\r\nFor a lot of incidents, the WRC used the reasoning that it\'s better to use an extra attempt where the procedure was correctly followed over an existing attempt where there was a problem with the procedure.\r\nThe WRC used this reasoning for PBQ Oshawa 2019, where an extra was available and used over the existing attempt.','2018-04-18 16:45:59','A judge forgot to hold a sheet between the competitor\'s face and the puzzle (extra available)','2025-05-21 14:26:50'),
(22,'2018-04-18 16:56:39',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated. The outcome of this incident wouldn\'t change, but how it should be handled is now explicitely stated in the regulations. \r\n\r\nA competitor broke the European Record in his fourth attempt the second round of 3x3x3 One-Handed. When trying to reconstruct the solve, it was discovered that the puzzle was not scrambled correctly (one move in the middle of the scramble was missing). The competitor was granted a provisional extra attempt at the competition.\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to replace the original attempt with the extra attempt.','2018-04-18 16:56:46','3x3x3 One-Handed Attempt was identified as misscramble ','2025-05-21 14:32:03'),
(23,'2018-04-23 09:31:09','2018-06-08 09:49:52',1,NULL,NULL,'In 4x4x4, first round, a competitor got excited about his result and briefly touched the puzzle immediately after stopping the timer.\r\n\r\nSince the touch was unintentional, the solve will not be penalized. The A6e rule will be updated to comply with this ruling. ','2018-04-27 23:04:34','A competitor briefly touched the puzzle immediately after stopping the timer','2018-06-08 09:49:52'),
(24,'2018-06-06 06:19:38',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'While re-generating scrambles for the 1st round of Pyraminx to accommodate a larger number of competitor groups, the Delegate accidentally used a version of TNoodle from 3 years ago (0.9.0). This version of TNoodle generates a different distribution of Pyraminx scrambles from the current version (0.13.3). Although it is unclear if this could have had a significant impact on competitors in this particular case, there is no general way to decide whether competitors may have received an advantage in an incident like this. As a result, the WRC has decided that [Regulation 4f](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4f) applies to this incident without exception, invalidating results from affected people in the first round of Pyraminx from YJ Fest 2018.\r\n\r\nNote: TNoodle contains a mechanism to contact the WCA website and detect if it is out of date, but this mechanism cannot detect if it is out of date when the computer is not connected to the internet (which is common at competitions). Individuals generating scrambles are reminded to take care and make sure they have the latest version of TNoodle on hand.\r\n\r\nWe know that this is a harsh decision that affects a significant number of competitors. However, the integrity of scrambles in WCA competitions is essential and the mission of the WCA states that we must strive for fair and equal conditions.','2018-10-03 10:11:23','Old version of TNoodle used for Pyraminx scrambles','2020-05-04 18:12:59'),
(25,'2018-07-28 18:34:11',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER*: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated. The outcome of this incident wouldn\'t change, but how it should be handled is now explicitely stated in the regulations. \r\n\r\n\r\nA competitor broke the single World Record the first round of 3x3x3 One-Handed. It was later found that the cube was not scrambled correctly.\r\n\r\nOriginal scramble: L2 D F2 D2 F2 L2 R2 D F U2 F\' R\' B2 F D\' B2 L2 R\'\r\nGiven scramble: L2 D F2 D2 F2 L2 R2 D F U2 F\' R\' B2 F D\' B2 **L** R\'\r\n\r\nA provisional extra attempt was granted to the competitor. The WRC has decided to accept the result of the extra attempt as the official result because the given scramble was not an officially generated scramble.\r\n\r\nRelevant Regulations:\r\n[4b)](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b) Puzzles must be scrambled using computer-generated random scramble sequences.\r\n[4g)](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4g) After scrambling a puzzle, the scrambler must verify that the puzzle is scrambled correctly. If the puzzle state is wrong, the scrambler must correct it (e.g. by solving the puzzle and applying the scramble sequence again).\r\n\r\nThis decision is in line with several precedents.','2018-07-29 12:07:06','3x3x3 One-Handed Attempt was identified as misscramble','2025-05-21 14:33:56'),
(26,'2018-10-03 10:19:47',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During their Multi Blind attempt, a competitor accidentaly made a move on one of their cubes during the memorization phase.\r\n\r\nRule B3c) forbids to apply moves during the memorization (penalty : disqualification of the attempt), and is not superseded by other rules in the F article, so the whole attempt should be disqualified.\r\n\r\nHowever, the WRC found more fair to consider only that cube as unsolved, and let the competitor continue the rest of the attempt.','2018-10-03 10:19:52','Competitor made a move in the memorization phase of Multi Blind','2021-02-12 21:45:49'),
(27,'2018-10-03 10:40:44',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'In Clock finals, a competitor noticed while reconstructing their solves that every single pin was the opposite of what it should have been.\r\n\r\nAfter investigation, it appeared that all scramblers had a misconception about pin scrambling, and made that mistake through the whole round. \r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to keep the results of the round, since:\r\n1. it was not the competitors\' fault, and\r\n2. in this specific case, the random distribution of scrambles states was consistently preserved by the mistake.\r\nThe scrambles in the database were updated to reflect the actual scrambles received by the competitors.','2018-10-03 10:40:48','Scramblers made a consistent mistake in clock scrambling','2019-09-07 12:55:18'),
(28,'2018-10-10 09:23:39',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A bug in TNoodle 0.13.4 and earlier resulted in 86 Skewb scrambles for official competitions that were accidentally truncated. As a result, they were not generated in a way that satisfies the requirements in [Regulation 4b3](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b3). Of these scrambles, 73 were for [CubingUSA Nationals 2018](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/competitions/CubingUSANationals2018/). The WRC has decided to keep these results.\r\n\r\nAs described in [the TNoodle 0.13.5 announcement](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/posts/tnoodle-0-13-5):\r\n\r\n> Per the WCA Regulations, an official scramble sequence for Skewb must produce a random state ([4b3](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b3)) from those that require at least 7 moves ([4b3c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b3c)) to solve.\r\n> \r\n> In order to make it hard to distinguish scrambles with short solutions on a scramble sheet, TNoodle was designed to ensure that all generated Skewb scramble sequences are at least 11 moves (even if there is an optional solution with fewer moves). However, a thread safety bug in TNoodle before version `0.13.5` made it possible for scramble sequences to be truncated, such that:\r\n> \r\n> * a truncated scramble sequence would be used if it required at least 7 moves to solve (still satisfying Regulation 4b3c), but\r\n> * the truncation did not preserve the random scramble distribution (violating Regulation 4b3).\r\n> \r\n> More details are available [at the TNoodle project on GitHub](https://github.com/thewca/tnoodle/pull/368).\r\n> \r\n> An analysis of solution lengths for historical scrambles suggests that this did not affect the distribution of states for the vast majority of past competitions. However, it did result in a significant bias of states towards shorter optimal solutions for at least one major competition ([CubingUSA Nationals 2018](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/competitions/CubingUSANationals2018)), which led to the discovery of this bug. We would like to thank Sbastien Auroux for bringing it to our attention, and Tim Reynolds for working with Jeremy Fleischman to identify and prepare a fix for TNoodle over the past weekend.\r\n\r\nWe have also verified that scrambles for other puzzles were not affected by a bug like this.\r\n\r\nA full list of affected scrambles is available [here](https://github.com/SAuroux/wca-analysis/blob/master/results-scripts/scramble_validity_analysis/skewb_outliers_20181005.txt). In particular, the distribution of optimal solution length for Skewb scrambles at CubingUSA Nationals 2018 was as follows:\r\n\r\n| Optimal Solution Length | Expected # of scrambles | Actual # of scrambles |\r\n|-------------------------|-------------------------|-----------------------|\r\n| 7 moves                 | 20                     | 51                    |\r\n| 8 moves                 | 78                     | 84                    |\r\n| 9 moves                 | 93                     | 61                    |\r\n| 10 moves                | 5                      | 0                     |\r\n| 11 moves                | 0                      | 0                     |\r\n\r\nWe believe that the large number of attempts for the competition caused conditions for the bug to happen with higher likelihood on the computer that was used to generate scramble sequences for CubingUSA Nationals 2018.\r\n\r\nAlthough the impact on the scramble distribution is measurable, the WRC has decided to keep all Skewb results from the 86 truncated scrambles because:\r\n\r\n1. We do not believe that this bug was known to anyone, or purposely used by any organizers, Delegates, or competitors. This bug is the responsibility of the WRC and the WST.\r\n2. Delegates properly followed the Regulations by using the output of a current official version TNoodle without inspecting or analyzing the scrambles ahead of time, as required by [Regulation 4b1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b1).\r\n3. The scrambles all still required at least of 7 moves for an optimal solution.\r\n4. The affected results are not affected to the extent that the competitors received a clearly unfair advantage against future Skewb competitors.\r\n\r\nFor future incidents, please note that attempts should still be removed if their scramble sequences do not follow the Regulations because they did not come from a current official scramble program, as in the case of [an incident where an old version of TNoodle was used by accident](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/24).\r\n','2018-10-10 09:23:57','Truncated Skewb scrambles in versions of TNoodle version 0.13.4 and earlier','2019-09-07 12:55:00'),
(29,'2019-01-02 09:38:44',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'After their inspection, a competitor started their timer, then reset it, then started it again before making any move.\r\nRegulation [A4d](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A4d) states that the competitor starts the solve by removing their hands from the timer (thus starting the timer), which happened during the first time they started the timer.\r\nTherefore the competitor reset the timer before the puzzle was solved and the result should be DNF.\r\n\r\nFor the case which occurred during China Championship 2017, the WRC also considered that the timer lights were covered by tape. However since it was the competitor\'s fifth solve on the exact same timer, the WRC decided to change the result to DNF.','2019-01-02 09:38:53','A competitor started his timer twice','2019-01-02 09:38:53'),
(30,'2019-02-28 18:43:52',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A judge forgot to hold a sheet between the competitor\'s face and the puzzle. This was found after the end of the competition and no extra was granted.\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to accept the result as the video showed no sign of the competitor abusing the situation and it was not his fault.\r\n','2019-02-28 18:44:26','A judge forgot to hold a sheet between the competitor\'s face and the puzzle (extra not available)','2019-09-07 14:09:27'),
(31,'2019-03-11 02:23:44',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'Due to a miscommunication, Cavite Open 2 2018 did not have puzzle covers on hand. The organizers decided to use letter-sized paper and score sheets instead.\r\n\r\nVideo evidence confirms that significant portions of puzzles were visible to competitors and spectators before attempts. This violates Regulation A2c1:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A2c1)) The scrambler places a cover over the scrambled puzzle that makes it impossible for any competitors or spectators to see any part of the puzzle. The cover remains over the puzzle until the start of the attempt.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Guideline A2c1+) explicitly clarifies that paper or score sheets are not an acceptable substitute:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A2c1+)) REMINDER In the past, score sheets have been used to cover puzzles while leaving some sides exposed. This is no longer permitted.\r\n\r\nAlthough there is no evidence anyone specifically intended to cheat, this is a serious violation of scramble secrecy.\r\nPer Motion [04.2019.1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/documents/motions/04.2019.1%20-%20Board%20of%20Directors.pdf) 2.8 and [Regulation 8f](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#8f), all results from Cavite Open 2 2018 have been removed.','2019-03-11 02:23:57','Competition did not use proper covers for puzzles','2019-09-07 12:54:14'),
(33,'2019-06-03 10:19:07',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated. The outcome of this incident wouldn\'t change, but how it should be handled is now explicitely stated in the regulations.\r\n\r\nAt least one competitor received an incorrect Square-1 scramble which started with a \"cube shape\". Analysis shows that this provided the competitor a clear advantage for the attempt compared to any possible scramble for the attempt.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has concluded that such attempts should be disqualified, since:\r\n\r\n1) Starting with cube shape provides a significant advantage for virtually all competitors (vs. receiving a scramble several moves away from cube shape).\r\n2) This is a significant breach of scramble accountability. A qualified scrambler would never send out such a scramble by accident, since cube shape scrambles are conspicuously uncommon and a [check against the scramble image](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4g) would have clearly shown that the scramble was incorrect.','2019-08-20 06:58:24','Incorrect Square-1 scramble (cube shape)','2025-06-05 06:21:39'),
(34,'2019-08-24 08:58:53',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since resolution of this incident, the WRC has reconsidered it\'s stance on penalties given to competitors who received wrong information from a delegate. [This more recent incident](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/81) takes into account that more lenient stance in situations like this.\r\n\r\nDue to a miscommunication, a WCA Delegate allowed a competitor to use unplugged headphones for his first two Multi-BLD attempts instead of earplugs/earmuffs.\r\n\r\nThis violates Regulation 2i):\r\n\r\n> [2i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i)) While competing, competitors must not use electronics or audio equipment (e.g. cell phones, MP3 players, dictaphones, additional lighting) apart from the Stackmat timer or stopwatch.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Guideline 2i1b+) explicitly clarifies that switched off devices are not allowed:\r\n\r\n> [2i1b+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#2i1b+)) CLARIFICATION This includes relevant devices which are switched off or disconnected.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Regulation [2t](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2t)) requieres the competitor to be familiar with the Regulations. Therefore the WRC decision is to change the affected attempts into **DNF**.\r\n\r\n','2019-08-28 07:02:48','A competitor used headphones for Multi-Blind','2025-05-15 06:47:37'),
(35,'2019-09-03 08:42:53','2019-11-06 21:03:33',1,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER:* Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated. The outcome of this incident wouldn\'t change, but how it should be handled is now explicitely stated in the regulations. \r\n\r\n\r\nA competitor broke the Algerian National Record in the final round of Pyraminx. The WDC found out that the puzzle was not scrambled correctly and the misscrable was clearly easier than the official scramble. The competitor was granted a provisional extra attempt at the competition.\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to replace the original attempt with the **extra** attempt.','2019-09-07 12:52:48','Pyraminx attempt was identified as misscramble','2025-05-21 14:32:45'),
(36,'2019-09-03 08:54:28','2019-11-06 21:03:52',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor briefly used his phone to take a photo of his Fewest Moves solution sheet just before giving it to the Delegate. Although the competitor didn\'t try to use it for cheating; it\'s a clear violation of regulation 2i).\r\n\r\n> [2i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i)) While competing, competitors must not use electronics or audio equipment (e.g. cell phones, MP3 players, dictaphones, additional lighting) apart from the Stackmat timer or stopwatch.\r\n\r\nTherefore the WRC decision is to change the affected attempt into **DNF**.','2019-09-07 12:53:00','A competitor took a photo of his Fewest Moves solution sheet before giving it to the Delegate','2019-11-06 21:03:52'),
(38,'2019-09-04 15:29:55','2019-11-06 21:06:24',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor was given the scoresheet and skewb of another competitor\'s due to the competitors having similar names. The competitor did not notice until after the solve was done, as the name on the scorecard did not match the competitor\'s. This competitor was given an Extra.\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to replace the original attempt with the **extra** attempt.','2019-09-07 12:53:23','A competitor received another competitor\'s skewb and did not notice until the solve was done','2019-12-27 04:52:21'),
(39,'2019-09-04 16:58:56','2019-11-06 21:05:11',1,NULL,NULL,'During 4x4 Blindfolded, a competitor claimed that a duplicate scramble is given. Two other competitors went to check the scramble at the solving station, which is something only the Delegate should do. The other two competitors saw the scramble, which they hadn\'t received yet. \r\n\r\nAlthough competitors must not attempt to gain information about future scrambles, it was clear in this situation that the competitors made a mistake in trying to be helpful, and were not attempting to cheat by trying to check the scramble.\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to uphold the Delegate\'s decision, which was to generate **extra** scrambles for these competitors.','2019-09-07 12:53:11','Two competitors attempted to help investigate a duplicate scramble situation','2019-12-27 04:52:50'),
(40,'2019-09-12 20:03:52',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor who had made it to the 333 final asked that he do his average early, as the competitor had to leave for a flight. The WCA Delegates decided to accomodate his request as the competition wasn\'t running on time and the final was going to start well after it was scheduled to. While the second group of Megaminx was ongoing, the competitor did his average using the spare scrambles from 333 One Handed finals which had not been used.\r\n\r\nOther competitors missed the final as they had to leave too, however the WCA Delegates weren\'t made aware of this until finals were underway and the competitors had already left. Due to absent competitors, the WCA Delegates asked anyone remaining in the top 20 to compete.\r\n\r\nThe Guideline 1h++) recommends to use the same scrambles for finals:\r\n\r\n> [1h++](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#1h++)) RECOMMENDATION All attempts in the final round of an event, as well as all 3x3x3 Fewest Moves attempts, should have the same scramble sequences for all competitors (i.e. only 1 group).\r\n\r\nThe WRC recommend to use the same scramble for finals (as cited before) and to warn all competitors that may need to leave the venue early if there is an opportunity to compete earlier. The WRC would also like to encourage competitors to reach out to the WCA Delegate in case they need to leave the venue early by justified causes.\r\n\r\nAs [TNoodle](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/scrambles/) generates 333 and 333 One Handed the same, the WRC decided to **allow all these attempts**.','2019-09-13 17:45:11','A competitor was allowed to compete early in the 333 final and with different scrambles','2019-12-27 04:51:44'),
(41,'2019-09-22 05:38:47','2019-11-06 21:07:16',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor competed with a cube where one of the stickers on the red face was a distinguishable shade from the others. This violates Regulation 3d2):\r\n\r\n> [3d2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3d2)) The colors of the colored parts must be solid, with one uniform color per face. Each color must be clearly distinct from the other colors.\r\n\r\nThe competitor did 4 attempts with this cube, and then did the last attempt with a legal cube. When the WCA Delegate asked if the competitor wanted to replace the 4 solves with extras (using Regulation [3k2a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2a)), the competitor declined.\r\n\r\nAs the round had a cutoff, the competitor did not make the cutoff after his first two solves (as stated by [11e2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11e2)), so the WRC has decided to record the results as DNS, DNS. Because all competitor\'s attempts are considered DNS, the competitor has not started any attempt. Therefore, the competitor\'s result should be removed.','2019-10-19 19:14:10','A competitor did several attempts with an illegal puzzle without accepting the extra attempts','2021-03-20 22:42:49'),
(42,'2019-10-22 10:39:20',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor used a stickerless cube with a \"PVC coating\" on each colored part. The puzzle was accepted at the competition.\r\n\r\nSimilar cubes with non-transparent (black) stickers have previously been allowed, and the WRC has concluded that the PVC coatings do not give the competitor an advantage that [Regulation 3d](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3d)) and [Regulation 3h](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3h)) are meant to prevent.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the WRC has decided that it is reasonable for these puzzles to be permitted.\r\n\r\nThe WCA Regulations will be updated to clarify this.','2019-10-22 10:40:43','PVC coating on a stickerless cube','2020-04-20 19:34:11'),
(43,'2019-11-01 16:47:20','2019-11-06 21:14:10',1,NULL,NULL,'During Multi-BLD, a competitor submitted his puzzles to be scrambled, without writing down a declared number of cubes. The scramblers scrambled all the puzzles and wrote down it on the scorecard. When the competitor came to solve, he told the judge that he wanted to attempt a number of cubes lower than the amount submitted. The judge intended to give the competitor the amount that he said he wanted to attempt, but miscounted and gave the competitor the full amount of cubes that were sumbitted.\r\n\r\nThe WCA Delegate allowed the competitor to attempt the amount that he had claimed, rather than the amount that he had submitted. Due to the staff\'s mistake in counting the attempt, the delegate gave a provisional extra.\r\n\r\nAlthough the competitor said a different number later, he initially submitted all the puzzles and did not mark anything on the scoresheet. This violates Regulation H1a):\r\n> [H1a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#H1a)) Before an attempt, the competitor must submit to the organization team the number of puzzles (at least 2) they wish to attempt.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Regulation H1a1) explicitly clarifies that changing the number of puzzles is not allowed:\r\n> [H1a1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#H1a1)) A competitor is not permitted to change the number of puzzles after submitting their number to the organization team.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the WRC decision was to consider the total amount of cubes attempted as the original amount the competitor had submitted. ','2019-11-06 21:11:43','A competitor submitted a wrong number of puzzles for Multi-Blind','2020-04-11 18:02:59'),
(44,'2019-11-01 17:22:12','2019-11-06 21:14:49',1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since this was brought to the WRC\'s attention, regulation [2k6](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/full/#2k6) has been created, which makes it required for competitors to fullfill the requirements  (e.g. knowing how to solve the puzzle) of all events they are competing in.\r\n\r\nIt was recently brought to the WRC\'s attention that [Regulation A1c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A1c)) arguably does not apply to Fewest Moves under the current structure of the WCA Regulations, because Article E does not refer to Article A.\r\n\r\nHowever, one of the original motivations for Regulation A1c) was to allow Delegates to apply it to Fewest Moves, and the WRC has supported this intended use of A1c since its introduction.\r\n\r\nThe Regulations will be updated to reflect this, as well as clarifying that the allowed aids specified under [Regulation 2i1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i1)) are also allowed in Fewest Moves Solving.','2019-11-06 21:11:30','A1c and 2i1 apply in Fewest Moves Solving','2025-06-10 06:09:15'),
(45,'2019-11-14 20:50:51','2019-11-22 15:07:47',1,NULL,NULL,'In Skewb, a competitor touched the puzzle immediately after stopping the timer. When releasing the puzzle, it fell into the lap of the competitor and then it jumped back to the mat.\r\n\r\nThis violates Regulation A6e):\r\n> [A6e](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6e)) After releasing the puzzle, the competitor must not touch or move the puzzle until the judge has inspected the puzzle. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF). Exception: If no moves have been applied, a time penalty (+2 seconds) may be assigned instead, at the discretion of the judge.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Guideline A6e+) explicitly clarifies that this case is considered touching the puzzle:\r\n> [A6e+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A6e+)) CLARIFICATION If the puzzle falls into the lap of the competitor after stopping the timer, this is considered touching the puzzle.\r\n\r\nBy reviewing video evidences, the WRC determined that this case is not comparable with [this other](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/23) as the competitor in this incident noticeably touched the puzzle. The WRC concluded that it is appropriate to apply a **+2 penalty** to the affected attempt.','2019-11-15 08:09:26','A competitor noticeably touched the puzzle immediately after stopping the timer','2019-12-27 04:42:37'),
(46,'2019-12-04 14:13:39','2019-12-14 23:26:23',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor claimed a attempt\'s result was incorrectly written and requested a result change.\r\nThe only video evidence available was a live stream video, which did not show a readable time on the display or the timer.\r\n\r\nThe original time written on the score sheet was accepted, because the result was both signed by the judge and the competitor and there was no reliable video evidence to support the result change.','2019-12-14 15:00:11','A competitor claimed an incorrect result was written down on the score sheet','2019-12-27 04:41:56'),
(47,'2019-12-13 21:08:15','2019-12-22 19:48:59',1,NULL,NULL,'The Organization Team used a small room for Fewest Moves Solving for a large number of competitors. This caused competitors to be very close to each other. This could have been used by competitors to cheat and look off another competitor\'s paper. \r\n\r\nHowever, the WRC has decided to **accept** the results because:\r\n1.  The WCA Delegates checked the solution sheets and saw that no competitors had the same solution.\r\n2.  The WCA Delegates carefully oversaw the competitors during the round.\r\n3.  There is no evidence that any competitors abused the situation to gain an unfair advantage.','2019-12-22 19:48:55','An inproper room was used for Fewest Moves Solving','2020-02-20 21:06:19'),
(48,'2019-12-13 21:20:42',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor did not sign for an attempt in R2 and did not qualify for the final round. This was discovered after the competition. This violates Regulation A7c4:\r\n> [A7c4](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7c4)) The competitor should not sign an attempt before the judge has recorded and signed the attempt. The competitor is ultimately responsible for ensuring that they and the judge have signed an attempt. If an attempt is found to be missing one or both signatures after the judge delivered the score sheet to the score taker (see [Regulation A7f](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7f)), it will be considered unfinished (DNF).\r\n\r\nAlthough the [Guideline A7c4+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A7c4+) allows a competitor to add a missing signature if it is found by the score taker. The missing signature was found after the competition and thus, the guideline does not apply here.\r\n\r\nThe WRC agreed that the original attempt should be a **DNF** and therefore the attempts from the finals should be removed. In addition, there is an existing [Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/19) that followed a similar reasoning.\r\n\r\nMore generally, this is what WRC decided to apply when results were wrongly entered, and someone mistakenly proceeded to the next round:\r\n\r\n- Keep the results if the competitor proceeded thanks to an error in someone else\'s results\r\n- Remove the results if the competitor proceeded thanks to an error in their own results','2019-12-22 19:51:01','A competitor did not sign for an attempt and did not qualify for the finals','2020-09-22 17:37:30'),
(49,'2019-12-13 21:30:20','2019-12-22 19:57:07',1,NULL,NULL,'During 3x3 Blindfolded Round 2, a competitor was using the nod-don technique. Immediately after the solve, he informed the WCA Delegates that he thought it might be a bit close to starting the first turn before the blindfold was fully donned. The WCA Delegates granted a provisional extra before asking the WRC for feedback. This might violate Regulations B4a) and B4b):\r\n\r\n> [B4a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B4a)) The competitor dons the blindfold to start the blindfolded phase.\r\n> \r\n> [B4b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B4b)) The competitor must not apply moves to the puzzle before they have fully donned the blindfold. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n\r\nSince the video evidence was not enough to know if the don is legit or not, the WRC agreed to accept the provisional **extra** as the valid result.','2019-12-22 19:57:02','The \"Nod-don\" technique was used for Blindfolded Solving','2019-12-27 03:52:34'),
(50,'2019-12-21 18:32:41',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor stopped the timer in a way that looked like it potentially violated the regulations (ie, with a \"karate chop\"). This violates Regulation A6d):\r\n\r\n> [A6d](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6d)) The competitor must stop the timer using both hands, placed flat on the sensors with palms down. Penalty: time penalty (+2 seconds).\r\n\r\nHowever, after analyzing the video evidence, the WRC has concluded that the bad timer stop is only visible if the video was analyzed frame-by-frame. Therefore, the WRC agrees that the original time **should not be penalized**. The WRC is also proposed a new policy for delegates using video evidence to apply potential penalites to solves. \r\n\r\n**The WRC updated their approach on frame-by-frame analysis on September 27th, 2024, clarifying other use cases. Whilst this does not affect this previous decision, more information can be found [here](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/posts/wrc-decisions-with-frame-by-frame-analysis).**\r\n','2019-12-22 19:54:27','A competitor stopped the timer with a \"karate chop\", only visible with video analysis','2024-10-25 19:59:19'),
(51,'2020-01-19 09:47:33','2020-03-31 20:27:29',1,NULL,NULL,'During the competitions, results on the scorecards were found to not match the results on the tournament displays. This was found after both the competitor and the judge signed the attempt. The WCA Delegate contacted with the competitor and the judge and concluded that the time was likely recorded incorrectly.\r\n\r\nThe Regulations A7b1) states that:\r\n> [A7b1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7b1)) If penalties are assigned, the judge records the original recorded time displayed on the timer, along with any penalties. (...)\r\n\r\nHowever, the WRC agreed to change the affected attempt to the one that was shown in the tournament display and that only varies in decimal (e.g. XX.X6 to XX.X7).\r\n\r\nGenerally, incidents regarding recording results from the tournament display follow this policy:\r\n\r\n1. The display is visible during a good part of the solve and seems to be working fine.\r\n2. It stops at a believable time (when the competitor stops the timer, + a little delay).\r\n3. The scoretaking mistake is understandable (e.g. The exact time is 10.507 and the judge wrote 10.57. If the display stops at 10.507 and the judge writes 10.53, there is most likely a display error and the recorded time on the scorecard is used).\r\n\r\nPlease notice that this is not a general ruling and the WRC strongly recommends to write the result directly from the Speed Stacks Stackmat timer. Tournament Displays are not recognized in the WCA Regulations and sometimes, do not match the time of the Speed Stacks Stackmat timer.','2020-01-30 20:24:45','A tournament display showed a different result from the one recorded on the scorecard','2020-03-31 20:27:29'),
(52,'2020-02-20 21:07:44','2020-03-31 20:28:34',1,NULL,NULL,'A Multi-Blind scheduled second attempt was found to have several duplicate scrambles because of an organizational mistake. The WCA Delegate provisionally changed some certain results to DNF that were surely duplicate scrambles.\r\n\r\nThe WRC agreed to **change the round format** from \"Best of 2\" to \"Best of 1\", because:\r\n\r\n1. All second attempts were found to be duplicate scrambles.\r\n2. It is not consistent to disqualify some competitors and not others arbitrarily for an organizational mistake.\r\n\r\nThis decision involves retroactively removing all second attempts.','2020-02-26 21:28:15','A Multi-Blind attempt was found to have several misscrambles','2020-03-31 20:28:34'),
(53,'2020-03-05 20:57:44',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A skewb final was found to have several misscrambles because of an organizational mistake. One scrambler was not familiar with skewb notation and accidentally scrambled wrongly some puzzles.\r\n\r\nAfter analyzing the video evidence, the WRC has concluded the amount of misscrambles significantly affected the final. The WRC agreed to change the round format **from three rounds to two rounds**, because:\r\n\r\n1. More than half of the attempts were found to be misscrambled.\r\n2. It is not consistent to disqualify some competitors and not others arbitrarily for an organizational mistake.\r\n3. The misscrambles were found to be noticeably different from the original scrambles.\r\n\r\nThis decision involves retroactively removing all second attempts. Therefore, the classification was decided with the results from the previous round.','2020-03-14 09:43:42','A Skewb round was found to have several misscrambles','2023-06-13 02:21:33'),
(54,'2020-03-20 13:39:32','2020-04-03 21:56:33',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor solved over 10 minutes in the 5x5x5 Blindfolded event. Due to a miscommunication, the judge did not use a stopwatch assuming that the competitor did not need it.\r\n\r\nAfter analyzing the video evidence, the WRC agreed to **use the original time** because:\r\n\r\n1. The time was near to 10 minutes so it was possible to estimate the time from the video.\r\n2. According to [Regulation 9f2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9f2), the result should be rounded to the nearest second.\r\n\r\nIn addition, a similar result was accepted at Nacional Perubik 2016 (see [Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/6)):\r\n\r\n> A competitor got a succesful 5x5x5 Blindfolded solve. The result wasn\'t written on the score sheet, but the competitor had recorded the solve, so the time was retrieved from the video and the result accepted as official.','2020-04-02 03:56:12','5x5x5 Blindfolded result without a backup stopwatch timing','2020-09-27 11:03:23'),
(55,'2020-04-03 22:10:11',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor signed for the wrong solve attempt. This is considered a DNS according to [Regulation A7c2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7c2)):\r\n\r\n> [A7c2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7c2)) If the competitor signs (or otherwise marks) an attempt before they have begun it, they forfeit the attempt and the result will be considered DNS.\r\n\r\nAs the competitor was experienced enough, the [Regulation A7g](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7g) is not applicable. Therefore the WRC agreed to changed the original attempt to **DNS**.\r\n\r\nFor the Altona Algorithms Attempt 2 2021 incident, the WRC agreed that this case is substantially different because:\r\n\r\n1. The competitor did not do it on purpose.\r\n2. The competitor notified the mistake to the WCA Delegate right after realizing it.\r\n3. It is clear that the competitor knows Article A\'s procedure and the importance of the signature. The competitor did not attempt to intentionally break the standard procedure not gain an unfair advantage.\r\n\r\nBecause of this, the WRC agreed to accept the original result for this incident.\r\n\r\nThe WRC would like encourage competitors to be familiar with the procedure of speedsolving ([Article A](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#article-A-speedsolving)). It is important to understand that the use of the signatures is not arbitrary but rather serves to identify the scramblers and judges and if the competitor agrees with the result.','2020-04-16 19:58:29','A competitor signed for the wrong attempt','2021-06-05 15:17:19'),
(56,'2020-04-29 19:58:00','2020-05-18 19:50:01',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor had been disqualified after an investigation by the WCA Disciplinary Committee found they were guilty of cheating in a WCA Competition over multiple rounds. Applying [Regulation 2j1a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2j1a)), the results of the first round of the competitor should be changed to DNF.\r\n\r\nThe WRC has decided that the results of the following rounds the competitor participated in should be removed, and not disqualified. [Regulation 9p2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9p2) states that the competitors who advance to the next round must be determined by ranking or by result in the preceding round. \r\n\r\nTherefore, as the competitor does not have a valid result in the first round, he doesn\'t meet the requirements for advancing to the next round and should not have competed in it.\r\n\r\nThe WRC understands that this decision is the best for maintaining consistency of the Regulations. The results should be removed because they were null and void, and not voidable, as they didn\'t meet the requirements to have happened in the first place.\r\n\r\nThis is also consistent with the decision taken on [this Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/48), in which the WRC decided to remove, and not disqualify, the results of a competitor in a round of an event they shouldn\'t have competed in due to a mistake they made in a previous round.\r\n\r\nAs a side effect, this stance could reduce the number of possible competitors that are able to advance to the subsequent rounds due to the [Regulation 9p1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9p1):\r\n\r\n> [9p1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9p1)) At least 25% of competitors must be eliminated between consecutive rounds of the same event.\r\n\r\nAs a consequence, some competitors, as has happened in the past, could hypothetically not have advanced to the following round and their results should have been removed.\r\n\r\nTo prevent those innocent competitors from being harmed by the disqualification of the results of a competitor in an incident they were not involved in, the WRC has agreed to preserve their results, regardless of the number of competitors being able to advance in a previous round.\r\n\r\nThis is also consistent with the precedent set on [this Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/48), as follows:\r\n\r\n> More generally, this is what WRC decided to apply when results were wrongly entered, and someone mistakenly proceeded to the next round:\r\n> - Keep the results if the competitor proceeded thanks to an error in someone else\'s results\r\n> - Remove the results if the competitor proceeded thanks to an error in their own result\r\n\r\nAs this has become a reoccurring incident, the Regulations will be updated to reflect this understanding of a flexible interpretation of Regulation 9p1 in the special circumstances here described.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, as this is the first time the WRC has adopted this stance, this understanding should not be applied retroactively, but only on incidents that happen from now on. ','2020-05-06 23:05:01','A WDC decision affected a competitor\'s results on multiple rounds','2020-09-22 17:38:14'),
(57,'2020-09-22 16:09:58','2021-01-08 21:16:00',1,NULL,NULL,'Due to a miscommunication, Kharkiv Open 2019 did not have puzzle covers for Clocks on hand. Because of the lack of covers, some judges used a score sheet for the Clock round.\r\n\r\nVideo evidence confirms that different judges used score sheets during the Clock round. This violates Regulation A2c1:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A2c1)) The scrambler places a cover over the scrambled puzzle that makes it impossible for any competitors or spectators to see any part of the puzzle. The cover remains over the puzzle until the start of the attempt.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Guideline A2c1+ explicitly clarifies that paper or score sheets are not an acceptable substitute:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A2c1+)) REMINDER In the past, score sheets have been used to cover puzzles while leaving some sides exposed. This is no longer permitted.\r\n\r\nAlthough there is no evidence anyone specifically intended to cheat, this is a serious violation of scramble secrecy. Following the Cavite Open 2 2018 precedent (see [Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/31)), the WRC agreed that the **Clock round should be removed**.','2020-09-30 21:02:23','Proper puzzle covers were not used for a Clock round','2021-01-08 21:16:00'),
(58,'2020-09-22 17:39:57','2021-07-01 20:42:52',1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, regulation 2j1a has been changed and now allows for results to be entered as DNS rather than DNF, if the competitor has not yet succesfully completed a solve in the round he is disqualified for.\r\n\r\nA competitor was disqualified from a round by the WCA Delegate for not doing their judging tasks. Following Regulation 2j1a, the results should be recorded as a DNF:\r\n\r\n> [2j1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2j1)) If a competitor is disqualified from an event for any reason, they are not eligible for any more attempts in the event.\r\n> [2j1a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2j1a)) The results of all remaining attempts in the event are recorded as DNF.\r\n\r\nHowever, the WRC found that because the competitor was disqualified before any of their attempts, this fits the definitions of Regulation 9f5 and Guideline 9f5+:\r\n\r\n> [9f5](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9f5)) The result of an attempt is recorded as DNS (Did Not Start) if the competitor is eligible for an attempt but declines it.\r\n> [9f5+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#9f5+)) (...). If the competitor did not qualify for an attempt (e.g. in a cutoff round), they have no result for the attempt.\r\n\r\nFollowing the reasoning of BCM Arya Cubing Challenge 2019 incident (see [Incident Log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/56)) and according to [Guideline 9f5+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#9f5+), the WRC agreed that the **competitor\'s result should be removed**. The Regulations will be updated to clarify this.\r\n\r\n','2020-10-05 20:43:00','A competitor was disqualified before their attempts','2025-06-10 06:47:14'),
(59,'2021-01-11 03:55:48','2021-07-01 20:42:43',1,NULL,NULL,'Currently, in Fewest Moves Solving, the stickers can be used as indicators on a puzzle:\r\n\r\n> [E3](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#E3)) The competitor may use the following objects during the attempt. Penalty for using unauthorized objects: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n> [E3c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#E3c)) Stickers (self-supplied).\r\n\r\nOther forms of indicator are allowed as long as the indicators does not break other WCA Regulations. For example, using a 3x3x3 Cube that has tiles that allow blocks (e.g. LEGO blocks) to be placed on them like stickers, is legal as long as it does not break other WCA Regulations. It is okay to use these blocks as indicating pieces by assembling instead of sticking to the puzzle surfaces. \r\n\r\nHowever, due to [Regulation E3e](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#E3e), the puzzle and the indication pieces should be approved by the WCA Delegates before being used in the Fewest Moves. The WCA Delegate should make sure the puzzles and the blocks are not illegal (e.g. contain electronic aids or might give an unfair advantage).\r\n\r\n\r\n','2021-03-10 00:34:16','Use of a 3x3x3 Cube with LEGO Pieces instead of stickers in Fewest Moves Solving','2021-07-01 20:42:43'),
(60,'2021-04-25 12:54:51',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During a 3x3 round, a piece popped out of a competitor\'s cube and a first-time runner picked it up and handed it to the competitor, which is not what [Guideline A5b++](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A5b++) calls for. An extra attempt was provided by the WCA Delegates because this was the runner\'s fault and not the competitor\'s since the competitor did not ask the runner to pick it up and the runner did this by themselves.\r\n\r\nThe WRC found a DNF to be too harsh for this particular case. As a result, the extra attempt should be used for the following reasons:\r\n\r\n1. The extra follows the correct procedure.\r\n2. It was not competitor\'s fault.\r\n3. The competitor did not attempt to gain an unfair advantage.\r\n\r\nIn case the original time was available, that original result should have been used. The reasoning for using the original time is to find a compromise between a DNF (which too harsh for something the competitor did not ask for) and an extra (which too kind because the solve with a pop was presumably bad).\r\n','2021-05-05 21:12:57','A runner picked up a popped piece during a competitor\'s attempt','2021-05-05 21:12:57'),
(61,'2021-04-25 14:04:19',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'In a competitor\'s video for a 3x3x3 Cube attempt, the competitor over-inspected (around 17.1s), but no call outs of 8 or 12 seconds at the correct timestamp were heard in the video.\r\n\r\nThe initial decision was to DNF this solve, but the decision was overturned by the WCA Board after an appeal. The WCA Board decided that it was more fair to let the result stand.\r\n\r\nThis was done because of the following:\r\n\r\n1. The error was made by the judge and the competitor is not at fault for overinspecting.\r\n2. The competitor may have gained an advantage, but potentially may not have. This is because it is not uncommon for competitors to begin solving when they hear the \"8 second\" warning, as this competitor did.\r\n3. Because the mistake was made by the judge, an extra should have been provided. However, since an extra was not available, the original time shall stand.\r\n4. A DNF is overly harsh for this situation and accepting the time achieved is more fair.','2021-05-05 21:12:43','A competitor\'s video showed an over-inspected solve without any time callouts by the judge','2021-05-05 21:12:43'),
(62,'2021-09-17 17:05:39',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'The competitor had two center caps fall off at the end of a 7x7x7 solve. The judge then asked a WCA Delegate whether the competitor had to place the caps on before finishing the attempt, and the WCA Delegate believed that it was fine, but was going to check with the WCA Regulations just to be sure. After the WCA Delegate realized that they were wrong about their initial claim, the competitor had already stopped the timer without the caps on. \r\n\r\nWhile a provisional extra was provided to the competitor, the solve was deemed a **DNF** because the WCA Delegate initially did not have a definitive answer.','2022-01-13 22:17:23','A competitor asked whether ending an attempt with a certain cube state was legal and got an indefinite response','2024-03-22 01:06:45'),
(63,'2022-07-12 18:46:23',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During the inspection of a Megaminx attempt, the competitor caused an unintentional misalignment to the puzzle, possibly against regulation [A3c1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A3c1).\r\n\r\nAfter careful review of the video footage ([11f](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11f)), the WRC has decided not to DNF the attempt. None of the frames analyzed point to the face having moved beyond the allowed 36 ([10f2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#10f2)).','2022-07-12 18:55:49','A competitor unintentionally caused a misalignment during Megaminx inspection','2023-01-11 12:45:58'),
(65,'2022-07-27 16:17:33',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor who used the nod-don technique contacted the delegate after the competition because he thought he may have been close to starting the first turn before the blindfold was fully donned (possibly against regulations [B4a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B4a) and [B4b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B4b)).\r\n\r\n> B4a) The competitor dons the blindfold to start the blindfolded phase.\r\n\r\n> B4b) The competitor must not apply moves to the puzzle before they have fully donned the blindfold. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n\r\n\r\nAfter analyzing video evidence at full speed, the WRC came to the conclusion that the competitor is not likely to have gained an advantage, thus allowing the solve to remain valid.','2022-08-10 22:14:02','The \"Nod-don\" technique was used for Blindfolded Solving (extra not available)','2022-08-10 22:14:02'),
(66,'2022-07-28 16:39:49','2023-02-07 14:45:21',1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: As of 2025, there is now a specific regulation, regulation [3h4d](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/full/#3h4d), allowing logos to be placed anywhere on the clock, so long as it doesn\'t obstruct the inner clock faces\r\n\r\nA competitor used a Clock with a sticker (logo) placed on the side (different from the flat surfaces of the puzzle).\r\n\r\nThe puzzle was determined to be competition-legal as per the following arguments:\r\n\r\n1. There are no regulations explicitly forbidding logos for Clock puzzles (as long as the logo does not provide any advantage, at delegate\'s discretion).\r\n2. The WRC concluded that the competitor is not likely to have gained an advantage because of the logo.\r\n','2022-08-10 22:22:52','A competitor used a Clock with a sticker (logo) placed on the side','2025-06-05 06:08:39'),
(67,'2022-07-29 16:00:21',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated to provide stricter criteria for when a misscramble should receive an extra.\r\n\r\nAfter the competition, a Square-1 attempt was identified as misscramble.\r\nAs an extra was not available and due to the fact that the misscramble was easier than the official scramble, the WRC decided to DNF the attempt.','2022-08-10 22:19:23','Square-1 attempt was identified as misscramble (extra not available)','2025-05-15 07:00:27'),
(69,'2022-11-08 22:15:13','2023-02-07 14:45:43',1,NULL,NULL,'A competitor claimed to be distracted in a 4x4x4 Blindfolded attempt with a DNF result, after finishing the solve, but before finishing the attempt (before signing the score sheet). Delegates granted the competitor an extra attempt as per [Regulation 11e](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11e).\r\n\r\nWRC further discussed this incident and agreed that the **original attempt should stay**. \r\n\r\nWhen an incident occurs during the attempt, a competitor has three options, each with their own benefits and risks:\r\n1. Immediately stop the attempt and request the extra.\r\n2. Keep the attempt running and appeal for an extra, as per [Guideline 11e+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#11e+).\r\n3. Finish the attempt and then try to request the extra.\r\n\r\nWRC highly recommends the competitors to choose the first or the second option as the WCA Delegate will be able to better determine the fairness of the appeal and exclude the possibility that the competitor based their request on the result of their solve.\r\n','2022-12-07 14:45:33','A competitor asked for an extra after stopping the timer','2023-02-07 14:45:43'),
(70,'2022-11-24 19:47:24','2022-12-07 16:20:43',1,NULL,NULL,'At Hanoi Open 2022, score sheets were used instead of appropriate cube covers for certain events (Clock, Pyraminx, and Megaminx) in violation of Regulation A2c1:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A2c1)) The scrambler places a cover over the scrambled puzzle that makes it impossible for any competitors or spectators to see any part of the puzzle. The cover remains over the puzzle until the start of the attempt.\r\n\r\nGuideline A2c1+ also explicitly prohibits the use of score sheets as covers:\r\n\r\n> [A2c1+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A2c1+)) REMINDER In the past, score sheets have been used to cover puzzles while leaving some sides exposed. This is no longer permitted.\r\n\r\nAlthough there is no evidence that anyone actively tried to cheat, the WRC agreed that this is a serious violation of scramble secrecy, therefore **all the results from Clock, Pyraminx, and Megaminx had been removed**. This decision also follows the precedent from Cavite Open 2 2018 (see this [incident log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/31)).','2022-12-07 15:41:47','Score sheets were used as cube covers in some events of a competition','2022-12-07 16:20:43'),
(71,'2022-11-24 21:03:59',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor qualified for the final round of an event. Upon checking data entry after the final round, but before the competition was over, an error was found which placed this competitor two positions beyond the original advancement conditions. \r\n\r\nThe Delegates provisionally decided to change the advancement conditions, increasing the number of competitors qualifying for the final round. Therefore, the competitors affected by this mistake could still compete. The WRC agreed with delegates\' decision as per [Regulation 9p2a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9p2a) because the decision was in compliance with [Regulation 9p1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9p1).','2022-12-07 14:36:29','A competitor should not have advanced to the next round upon the data entry error was found','2022-12-07 14:36:29'),
(72,'2022-11-25 22:45:11',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'After a competitor finished their solve, the timer was reset by either the judge (Montpellier Open 2022) or by the timer itself (Bay Area Speedcubin\' 29 PM 2022 and Rose City 2022) before the result was fully recorded on the score sheet. The video evidence showed the display but not the timer.\r\n\r\nSince the display was clearly shown in the evidence and it was working fine through the solve, WRC agreed that **the original result shown on the display may stand**.\r\n\r\nPlease note that as per Regulation A7b1 the result must always be recorded from the timer, but not from the display:\r\n\r\n> [A7b1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7b1)) If penalties are assigned, the judge records the original recorded **time displayed on the timer**, along with any penalties...\r\n\r\nThe time from the display may be accepted when the one from the timer is unavailable **only** under certain circumstances (see the following [incident log](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/51)).','2022-12-07 15:09:49','Timer was reset before the result was recorded (only video evidence showing the display was available)','2023-01-11 12:44:12'),
(73,'2022-11-27 09:28:43',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since resolution of this incident, clarification [A6e++ ](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/full/#A6e++) was introduced, which provides clarity on how to resolve such an incident.\r\n\r\nA competitor was stopped right at the 60 minute time limit in 3x3x3 Multi-Blind holding a solved puzzle. In other words, the competitor was holding the puzzle when the judge stopped the timer, so a time penalty (+2 seconds) was applied following Regulation A6c:\r\n\r\n> [A6c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6c)) The competitor must fully release the puzzle before stopping the timer. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF). Exception: If no moves have been applied after stopping the timer and before releasing the puzzle, a time penalty (+2 seconds) may be assigned instead, at the discretion of the judge.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the competitor was also touching the puzzle after stopping the timer without applying any moves, so another time penalty (+2 seconds) should have been applied as per Regulation A6e2:\r\n\r\n> [A6e2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6e2)) Penalty for touching the puzzle after stopping the timer without applying any moves: time penalty (+2 seconds)...\r\n\r\nHowever, the WRC agreed that: the regulations cited above are unclear regarding the correct way to apply the penalties and the spirit of these regulations is to prevent the competitor from applying moves upon and/or after stopping the timer. Therefore, the attempt was penalized following Regulation A6c only.\r\n\r\n','2022-12-07 15:27:44','A competitor was stopped at the time limit holding a solved puzzle in 3x3x3 Multi-Blind','2025-06-01 21:26:48'),
(74,'2022-11-27 09:49:47',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor contacted the WCA Delegate several days after the competition reporting that one piece of their puzzle had a sound slightly distinguishable from other pieces and that another piece coating  was different from other pieces. Both things were found after the competition. The competitor provided video evidence to show the difference. They used this puzzle during their 3x3x3 Blindfolded attempts. \r\n\r\nThe WRC agreed that **the results should be kept as is** for the following reasons:\r\n\r\n1. The sound is very lightly distinguishable even in silence, which is not the case in a competitive environment, even during Blindfolded Solving events. \r\n2. The competitor analyzed the sound difference only after the competition, so there was no defined advantage during the competition. The video of the attempts also showed that the competitor\'s solving speed could not allow to apply the moves based on the sound and/or texture.\r\n3. The texture was considered reasonable by the WCA Delegate at the competition. Regulation 3j1 allows it:\r\n\r\n> [3j2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3j1)) Puzzles are permitted to have reasonable wear, at the discretion of the WCA Delegate.','2022-12-07 19:17:51','One piece of the puzzle was found slightly distinguishable after the competition','2022-12-07 19:17:51'),
(75,'2022-11-27 15:56:35',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competition staff member competed in 5x5x5 Blindfolded one day prior to the event. Mistakenly, the scrambles that were used for their attempts were reused for one of the next groups. The scrambles were seen by two competition staff members and one competitor who was not competing in that group.\r\n\r\nAs per Regulation 4b4, the scrambles **should** be applied during a maximum time frame of 2 hours:\r\n\r\n> [4b4](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#4b4)) Each scramble sequence should be applied during a maximum time frame of 2 hours. This time frame starts when the scramble sequence is applied for the first time.\r\n\r\nThe WCA Delegates granted the competitors provisional extra attempts. \r\n\r\nSince scramble secrecy is not guaranteed here and even though Regulation 4b4 wording is \"should\'\', scramble secrecy must be treated seriously. Due to the reasons above, WRC agreed that **the extra attempts should be kept**. ','2022-12-07 19:10:37','Scrambles were accidentally reused','2022-12-07 19:10:37'),
(77,'2022-12-07 16:25:49',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During a Fewest Moves attempt a competitor\'s phone alarm went off. The competitor took out their phone and turned off the alarm. The WCA Delegate confirmed that the competitor used their phone only to turn it off.\r\n\r\nRegulation 2i states:\r\n> [2i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i)) While inspecting or solving, competitors must not use electronics or audio equipment (e.g. cell phones, MP3 players, dictaphones, additional lighting) apart from the Stackmat timer or stopwatch.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, Regulation 2i4 states:\r\n> [2i4](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i4)) Competitors should turn off all cell phone notifications while competing to avoid disturbing the competition.\r\n\r\nStrictly applying the Regulations, the competitor\'s attempt must have been disqualified (DNF) as they interacted with their phone (an electronic device). However, the WRC agreed that the attempt should stay for the following reasons:\r\n\r\n1. The competitor only turned off the alarm, no advantage was gained.\r\n2. If the alarm continued to be on, other competitors may have been disturbed, which could lead to serious consequences.\r\n\r\nThe WRC recommends competitors and WCA Delegates to be more careful with electronic devices and to turn them off to avoid similar situations.','2022-12-07 16:26:31','A competitor turned off an alarm during a Fewest Moves attempt','2023-06-23 03:11:55'),
(78,'2022-12-22 22:31:30',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During Please Be Solved Vancouver 2022 (Jul 24, 2022) and Silver Spring Summer 2022 (Aug 13, 2022), a judge forgot to hold a sight blocker for a significant amount of time in a 3BLD attempt.\r\n\r\nIn both cases, the decision from the WCA Regulations Committee was to keep the extra attempt. However, in the latter, the decision was overturned by the WCA Board of Directors, thus keeping the original attempt.\r\n\r\nThe WCA Board of Directors provided the following reasons:\r\n>  1.  No change in the execution speed or positioning of the competitor\'s head to indicate that they were looking at the cube initially.\r\n>  2.  The speed is in line with the competitor\'s abilities per previous competitions which were without incidents.\r\n>  3.  It is not the fault of the competitor, but the judge. No actions from the competitor lead to the impression of cheating or even trying to gain an advantage from the situation.','2023-01-09 20:02:29','A judge forgot to hold a sight blocker for a significant amount of time in a 3x3x3 Blindfolded attempt','2023-02-06 09:35:58'),
(79,'2023-01-09 20:41:33','2023-02-07 14:45:30',1,NULL,NULL,'Through the years (2013-2022), several Regulations and Guidelines were violated in many competitions in Vietnam. This included:\r\n\r\n* Using illegal timers (previous Regulation 8a7, now Regulation 7f1a violated)\r\n* Using score sheets instead of cube covers (Regulation A2c1 and Guideline A2c1+ violated)\r\n* Using Stackmat timers that are not attached to mats (Regulation 7f2 violated)\r\n* Inspection not measured due to missing stopwatches (Regulation A3b2 violated)\r\n* Blank competitor\'s fields in score sheets (Regulation A7c4 should lead these attempts to be changed to DNF)\r\n* Spectators staying right up against the solving stations (Regulation 7b violated)\r\n* Scrambling area not isolated at all\r\n\r\nAfter investigating each competition based on the delegate reports and publicly available evidence, the  WRC agreed to keep/remove the results based on the following criteria, where removing results supersedes keeping them:\r\n\r\n* Competitions using unattached/missing mats - keep results.\r\n* Illegal timers: remove all results from affected competitions.\r\n* Score sheets instead of covers:\r\n  * Prior to 2013, keep all results.\r\n  * 2013 onwards, remove all results from affected rounds.\r\n\r\nThe decision was approved by the WCA Board of Directors. \r\n\r\nFor more details, see [this](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1E-J8WRfld6mpbHslM3rW10fNSsXgkl2y/view?usp=share_link) investigation report and [this](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/posts/wrc-investigation-vietnamese-competitions-results-removal) announcement. See [this](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/70) related incident.','2023-01-29 18:03:43','Major scramble secrecy and solving procedure issues','2023-02-07 14:45:30'),
(80,'2023-01-26 16:26:14',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'At Vancouver Island 2019, a Yuxin timer was used during official attempts of several events. The WRC decided to disqualify the rounds where it was used, namely, 3x3x3 Cube, 4x4x4 Cube, 5x5x5 Cube, 3x3x3 One-Handed, and Megaminx.\r\n\r\nPer Regulation 8a7 ([2018-01-01](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/history/official/2018-01-01/) WCA Regulations version; now declared by [Regulation 7f1a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#7f1a)) only Speed Stacks Stackmat timers were allowed to be used at official competitions.\r\n\r\n> 8a) An official WCA competition must:\r\n...\r\n8a7) Use the authentic Speed Stacks Stackmat timer (Generation 2, Generation 3 Pro Timer, or Generation 4 Pro Timer) for time measurement.\r\n\r\nThe main reason for disallowing Yuxin timers is their quality, in particular they sometimes can run with a different speed and measure times incorrectly, which might be not noticeable, especially during fast events.','2023-01-27 17:49:18','Non-permitted timers were used','2023-01-27 17:49:18'),
(81,'2023-02-07 15:15:48',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During a FMC attempt, the only listed WCA Delegate assigned some of his responsibilities to the judge (the Delegate asked competitors to make questions to the judge), as per [Regulation 1c](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#1c). For this reason, two competitors asked the judge about rotations during the attempt, and both received wrong information. One of the competitors initially got a DNF because of the wrong rotation, and the other one got a DNF regardless of the rotation.\r\n\r\n**The final decision was to consider the rotations wrote by the competitors as if they were correct**. Therefore, if the involved competitors wrote z, then the rotation was considered as z\', because that is what the competitors would have written if they had received the correct information. The decision from the WCA Regulations Committee had the following reasons (among others explained privately):\r\n\r\n1. Although competitors must be familiar with the WCA Regulations as per Regulation [2t](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2t), the WRC considers that a WCA Delegate (in this case the judge representing the authority of the Delegate) telling wrong information overrides this regulation, in this particular situation.\r\n2. In FMC attempts, delegates and judges **may** give clarifications about the Regulations (see Regulation [E5](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#E5)). If they decide to give clarifications (because they consider that the question is reasonable and they know the answer to the question), the clarification **must** be correct.','2023-09-21 02:51:05','Fewest Moves judge provided wrong information about the WCA Regulations (Delegate unavailable)','2023-09-21 02:51:05'),
(82,'2023-04-07 10:52:46',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During a Fewest Moves attempt, a competitor went to the bathroom in the middle of their attempt and returned a few minutes later.\r\n\r\nThe result was a DNF either way. However, the WRC agreed that it is fine to allow competitors to go to the bathroom during the attempt, as long as the WCA Delegate can ensure that the competitor will not attempt to cheat. ','2023-04-08 03:47:59','A competitor went to the bathroom during a Fewest Moves attempt','2023-04-08 03:47:59'),
(83,'2023-04-25 10:55:16',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, the [regulation 2i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i) has been updated to provide more insight on what is permitted and not permitted regarding electronic usage.\r\n\r\n\r\nA competitor was carrying a handheld microphone which was used for announcements during the competition. During a solve he had it lying on the table where it started to roll. He grabbed the microphone to make sure it did not fall off the table. Regulation 2i states:\r\n\r\n> 2i) While inspecting or solving, competitors must not use electronics or audio equipment (e.g. cell phones, MP3 players, dictaphones, additional lighting) apart from the Stackmat timer or stopwatch. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n\r\nGiven that the competitor was not **using** the microphone, he did not break this regulation. The solve was therefore ruled as OK.\r\n\r\n','2023-05-03 02:56:19','A competitor grabbed a microphone during an attempt, to prevent it from falling','2025-05-11 17:06:36'),
(84,'2023-04-25 11:07:37',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Please note that as of 2025, [A2e2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A2e2) explicitly prohibits the competitor from lifting the cover with associated DNF penalty.\r\n\r\n> A3b2) The competitor starts the attempt by confirming that they are ready, and the judge uncovers the puzzle and starts timing the inspection.\r\n\r\nThe competitor said \"ready\" to the judge before inspection, but the judge did not uncover the puzzle. From a video of the incident, it can be seen that the competitor looks visibly confused and stressed after the judge did not uncover the cube. The competitor then lifted the cover themselves and began the solve shortly after. This was only discovered after the competition, meaning no extras were available. The WRC agreed to keep the original result without penalties, for the following reasons: The procedural error was the judge\'s fault, the video of the competitor showing he was thrown off by the situation, and no advantage gained (as the inspection time was within 15 seconds).\r\n\r\n','2023-05-03 03:24:14','A competitor uncovered their own puzzle, as the judge failed to do so','2025-06-01 21:25:18'),
(85,'2023-04-30 18:09:51',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: As of 2025, regulation [A5a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A5a) has been updated, giving an exception to competitors who do not gain any advantage from their communication.\r\n\r\nWhile the competitor was inspecting the puzzle, a person from the audience asked if they (the competitor) could solve their (the spectator\'s) puzzle. The competitor responded with \"yes, but later\". The competitor did not ask for an extra during the attempt. Technically, they communicated with someone other than the delegate and the judge during his attempt, which would be a violation of [Regulation A5a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A5a).\r\n\r\nThe regulation, as of February 15th 2023 stated the following:\r\n> A5a) While inspecting or solving the puzzle, the competitor must not communicate with anyone other than the judge or the WCA Delegate. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n\r\nThe WRC agreed to keep the result as it would be too harsh to DNF it, given that the competitor was just being kind with the young spectator. Furthermore, no advantage was gained from the communication. The regulation was also proposed to be more lenient for the next regulation cycle, to reflect this decision.','2023-05-03 03:32:49','A spectator communicated with a competitor during the competitor\'s inspection','2025-06-05 06:18:31'),
(86,'2023-06-02 21:14:39','2023-06-13 10:11:50',1,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER*: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated. The outcome of this incident wouldn\'t change, but how it should be handled is now explicitely stated in the regulations. \r\n\r\nDuring the competition, after the round was completed, scrambles were verified as a competitor broke a record.\r\n\r\n* At Hanoi Super Brain Zyo 2023, one of the attempts in 3x3x3 Cube was found to be misscrambled by the first move of the scramble, affecting only the last move of the solution.\r\n* At Michigan Speedcubing Spring 2023, one of the attempts in Pyraminx was found to be misscrambled by a tip affecting only one move of the solution.\r\n\r\nAlthough the solution was barely affected, and it was similar in difficulty in both cases, the voting among WRC members resulted in a decision to **keep the extra solve** following the standard misscrambles procedure.','2023-06-09 00:53:16','An attempt was found to be misscrambled by one move','2025-05-21 14:35:19'),
(87,'2023-06-02 21:19:46','2023-06-13 10:11:40',1,NULL,NULL,'*DISCLAIMER: The WCA Regulations and Guidelines relating to misscrambles have been updated since this incident was originally published. The approach described below should no longer be followed from January 1st, 2025.*\r\n\r\nAfter a competition, attempts from several competitors were found to be misscrambled. The WRC investigated each of those attempts to determine if they should stay based on the following criteria:\r\n\r\n* If the misscramble gives the competitor a significant advantage, the attempt should be changed to DNF.\r\n* If the misscramble is similar in difficulty to the original scramble, the attempt should be left as is.\r\n* If the misscramble cannot be analyzed (e.g. the video of the attempt is not available), the attempt should be left as is.\r\n\r\nPlease note that in case the misscramble is found during a competition, it must always be replaced with an extra attempt (see the Incident Log entry [here](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/86)).\r\n','2023-06-09 00:13:14','Attempt was found to be misscrambled after a competition (extra not available)','2025-05-15 06:58:37'),
(88,'2023-06-02 21:40:08','2023-06-13 10:11:31',1,NULL,NULL,'After a competition, a large number of misscrambles was found to be sent out during certain rounds of several events. In particular, a lot of misscrambles happened during 3x3x3 Cube Final, Pyraminx Final, and 3x3x3 One-Handed Final.\r\n\r\nAltghough many attempts during the mentioned rounds were done using correct scrambles, and therefore were valid, the outcome of the internal WRC voting was to **remove all affected rounds** as the number of misscrambles was large. The decision resulted in the removal of 3x3x3 One-Handed event, change in Pyraminx event format from two rounds to one round, and in the change in 3x3x3 Cube event format from three rounds to two rounds. See similar Incident Log entry [here](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/53).','2023-06-09 00:16:18','Several rounds were found to have several misscrambles','2023-06-13 10:11:31'),
(89,'2023-06-02 21:56:39','2023-06-13 10:11:22',1,NULL,NULL,'After the competition, a competitor reported that they had both the scrambles from the previous group and from their (current) group in their average. The competitor was also a scrambler for the previous group. The WCA Delegate also confirmed they could have left two consecutive scramble sets open at the same time. \r\n\r\nSince the scramble secrecy was violated, the WRC agreed that **the results from the affected round should be removed** (also resulting in the removal of the final round).','2023-06-09 00:21:54','Scramble set from the finished group was re-used','2023-06-13 10:11:22'),
(90,'2023-06-02 22:12:05','2023-06-13 10:11:14',1,NULL,NULL,'WRC received some pictures that showed a cover made of thin white plastic that at some angles could provide some information about the scrambled states of puzzles. However, the WCA Delegates showed the WRC that they had stacked two covers one above the other in order to make them non-translucent and that some single covers were opaque enough to ensure scramble secrecy. \r\n\r\nWRC reviewed the video evidence from the public resources and agreed that the results **should be kept**. While this is not the safest way to cover the puzzles, the organizers and the WCA Delegates did ensure scramble secrecy by double stacking the covers.\r\n\r\n### Advice for the Community and Organizers:\r\nScramble secrecy is an extremely important and delicate matter. If you ever have any concern regarding scramble secrecy during a competition, the safest thing to do is to address the issue with the WCA Delegates of the competition. Breaches in the scramble secrecy may result in the removal of the affected rounds/attempts.','2023-06-09 16:50:02','Cube covers used for the competition were translucent','2023-06-13 10:11:14'),
(91,'2023-06-02 22:30:06','2023-06-13 10:11:04',1,NULL,NULL,'During inspection, a competitor reported that their timer was in 4-pad mode. As later discovered, the competitor touched their camera during the inspection violating [Regulation 2i2b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2i2b), before reporting the timer issue:\r\n\r\n> 2i2b) The competitor must not interact with (e.g. operate, hold, wear) any active camera. Exception: the competitor may wear a camera mounted on their head, as long as it is out of their sight and it is clear that they are not interacting with it (apart from wearing it).\r\n\r\nThe WCA Delegates granted a provisional extra attempt, but the WRC agreed to **keep the DNF** since the competitor touched the camera **before** reporting the issue with the timer. In general, WRC considers the order in which incidents happen to determine the attempt\'s result (for example, if the competitor had reported the timer issue first, the extra attempt would have been used).','2023-06-09 01:29:45','Two incidents happened during inspection','2023-06-13 10:11:04'),
(92,'2023-06-11 18:30:43',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: As of 2025, regulation [A6a1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6a1) has been updated, to allow competitors to stop the stopwatch themselves if their judge does not do so.\r\n\r\nA competitor finished their attempt and made the signal for the judge to stop the official stopwatch. However, as the judge was unavailable (i.e. too far from the station), the competitor decided to stop the stopwatch themselves (in violation of [Guideline 2i+](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#2i+)).\r\n\r\nDespite the fact that Guideline 2i+ would make this a DNF, **the WCA Regulations Committee agreed to keep the result**, based on the following points:\r\n\r\n* **Either the Delegate or the judge saw this situation (key point of consideration for the final decision).**\r\n* [Regulation B5b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B5b) was not followed by the judge.\r\n* The competitor had no intention to cheat nor gain an unfair advantage.\r\n* An extra is unnecessarily harsh and mentally draining for Big BLD and MBLD attempts.','2023-09-21 03:03:46','A competitor stopped the official stopwatch in a BLD attempt (judge unavailable to stop it)','2025-06-05 06:19:58'),
(93,'2023-06-16 23:19:06',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,'It was reported that several misscrambles were issued during the first round of the 3x3x3 Blindfolded event.\r\nGiven the substantial amount of affected attempts, the WRC deemed that the most consistent and fair decision was to remove all the results from the round. As the results were invalidated, it was no longer possible to determine the advancement conditions for the final round. Therefore, the results for any subsequent round were also invalid (and removed).\r\n\r\nFor more precedents, see the following incident logs: [#53](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/53) and [#88](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/88).','2023-09-21 03:05:08','A 3x3x3 Blindfolded round was found to have several misscrambles','2023-09-21 03:05:08'),
(97,'2024-02-27 20:42:12',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During 3x3x3 blindfolded attempt, a competitor donned the blindfold in such a way that they were able to see the judge but not the puzzle. The judge said that at some point of the blindfolded phase the competitor looked at them for a few seconds and then continued the execution.\r\n\r\n[Regulation B4b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#B4b) says:\r\n\r\n> B4b) The competitor must not apply moves or intentional changes in alignment to the puzzle before they have fully donned the blindfold. Penalty: disqualification of the attempt (DNF).\r\n\r\nSince the competitor was able to see the judge and other surrounding, the WRC decided that the blindfold was **not** fully donned, and therefore **the attempt should be changed to DNF**.','2024-02-28 12:15:20','A competitor did not fully don the blindfond but was not able to see the puzzle','2024-02-28 12:15:20'),
(98,'2024-03-01 11:08:09',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor called the WCA Delegate asking for an extra attempt, claiming that the judge lifted the cover without him indicating that he was ready. The WCA Delegate granted an extra attempt with the reasoning that no delegates were available at the moment the incident happened (one was competing, one was supervising the scrambling table, and one was outside the room). It was initially thought that the competitor only asked for an extra attempt after the solve was completed. \r\n\r\nThe WCA Delegates described their reasoning to the WRC. Initially, the WRC decided to revert the decision of the WCA Delegates and use the original attempt. The WRC based their decision on the following:\r\n\r\n* [Regulation 11e](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11e): \"... The competitor should appeal verbally or in writing to the judge and WCA Delegate *at the time of the incident*...\".\r\n* [Guideline 11e+++](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#11e+++): The WRC did not deem the circumstances exceptional enough based on the description of the WCA Delegates.\r\n* [Similar incident](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/69).\r\n\r\nThe WRC does not consider the Delegates being temporarily unavailable as an extreme circumstance that would result in an extra attempt. It would be near impossible for a Delegate to reach a competitor within their inspection period. As the incident happened at the very beginning of the inspection, the competitor should have stopped their inspection right away and waited for one of the Delegates to be available to request an extra attempt. \r\n\r\nBy following through with the solve, the competitor had the opportunity to decide whether or not they wanted an extra attempt based on their result on the original scramble. This is an unfair advantage that providing an extra attempt in this scenario provides, and this is exactly the reason for 11e+++.\r\n\r\nThis decision was appealed to the WCA Board. While processing the appeal, new evidence became available - it was found that the competitor did appeal to the judge when the cover was lifted early. The WCA Board decided to overturn the WRC decision, reinstating the extra attempt. The statement from the WCA Board can be found [here](https://forum.worldcubeassociation.org/t/wca-statement-regarding-yiheng-wangs-0-93-2x2-average/49637).\r\n\r\n','2024-04-27 00:22:23','The judge lifted the cover early and the competitor requested an extra attempt','2024-04-27 00:25:26'),
(100,'2024-04-10 15:35:45',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'During a solve, a competitor\'s timer malfunctioned and the tens-place digit of the timer suddenly changed from 1 to 0, thus causing 10 seconds to be deducted from the total time while the timer was running. The final recorded result of the attempt was consistent with the time shown on the malfunctioned timer. No extra attempt was given.\r\n\r\nAfter analyzing the footage utilizing framecounting, and an internal discussion, as well as consulting the WRT, the WRC has decided to **add 10 seconds to the original result** instead of issuing a DNF.','2024-04-24 01:49:38','Timer deducted 10 seconds off of total time while running','2024-04-24 01:49:38'),
(102,'2024-04-21 11:07:27',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, regulation [3k2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2) has been updated to better define how an incident like this should be handled.\r\n\r\nAt the start of round 2 it was noticed that a competitor had submitted an illegal puzzle that had also been used in the previous round. Their previous results were therefore changed to DNF, following [3k2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2). As this was the competitor\'s fourth competition they were granted a provisional extra round under [A7g](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7g).\r\n\r\nThe WRC decided that the round 1 results should remain DNF. Extra attempts can not be issued for round 1 using [3k2a](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2a) as the round had finished. As the second round had started and the original attempts were valid, [9l](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9l) also prevented extras being awarded for another reason, such as [A7g](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7g). The WRC acknowledges that the concept of an invalid attempt in [9l](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#9l) is not defined and will consider clarifying this in the next regulations cycle.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, had [A7g](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A7g) been available, the WRC\'s view is that it should not be applied to issue extra attempts in this situation as the competitor had enough competiton experience ([A7g++++](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#A7g++++)). While they may not have encountered this aspect of the WCA Regulations before, the same could be said in many situations, and competitors are expected to be familiar with the regulations ([2t](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#2t)).','2024-05-31 10:15:45','An illegal cube was discovered after a subsequent round had started','2025-06-06 09:13:40'),
(103,'2024-04-24 01:00:25',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor had a judge who misinterpreted a comment by the competitor as them indicating that they were \"ready\". The competitor immediately called a delegate and was granted an extra solve.\r\n\r\nLater, it was found that the judge was not calling out inspection times (8/12 seconds) for the first four solves. The competitor asked for the judge to be replaced for their fifth solve. \r\n\r\nThe delegates viewed video footage of the competitor\'s solves and deemed that the judge indeed did not call out 8/12 seconds. Additionally, the competitor had overinspected (above 15 seconds but below 17 seconds) for the second, third, and fourth solves. \r\n\r\nThe delegates and WRC agreed on the following ruling: the competitor was experienced enough and had enough chances to recognize that the judge was not calling out inspection times. The second, third, and fourth solves of the average (which had the overinspection) obtained a +2 penalty. ','2024-05-31 10:46:02','Judge did not call out inspection times, and competitor overinspected','2025-05-21 14:39:04'),
(104,'2024-04-24 01:20:48',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor was mistakenly given the second scramble for their first attempt. The second attempt was scrambled according to the second scramble (as the mistake was not yet known). Upon sitting down for the second attempt, the competitor accidentally knocked over the cover. The competitor then recognized and confirmed that they had received a duplicate scramble as it had matched the first attempt. \r\n\r\nThe finalized ruling was for the attempt to be DNFed. In this case, there were two mistakes that occurred simultaneously:\r\n1. the competitor obtained a repeat scramble\r\n2. the competitor accidentally knocked over the cube cover.\r\n\r\nHere, the predominant mistake was deemed to be 2. as the competitor did not know it was a repeated scramble when knocking it, even if accidentally.\r\n\r\nThe decision also aligns with the historical and commonplace interpretations of the differences between a DNS and a DNF, where a DNS is given when a competitor voluntarily removes themselves from an attempt, and a DNF is given for other mistakes. ','2024-05-31 10:50:29','Competitor accidentally knocked over cube cover and realized they got a duplicate scramble','2024-05-31 10:50:29'),
(105,'2024-05-02 00:58:08',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Since the resolution of this incident, the regulation [11i](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#11i) has been updated to provide stricter criteria for when a misscramble should receive an extra.\r\n\r\nAfter the final round of 3x3 Blindfolded, a delegate was approached by two competitors who informed the delegate that they had received misscrambled on their second solves. Both competitors had DNFed their second solves, and the scramble they received was said to be less straightforward than the true scramble. Video evidence of the misscramble was inconclusive due to poor quality. The delegate decided to give the competitors provisional extra attempts. \r\n\r\nThe decision was to use the delegate discretion and accept the extra attempts that the delegates provided. This situation is best understood by the delegates handling the incident as they are the best equipped to determine if the competitor truly received a misscamble.\r\n\r\nThis decision is similar to the one outlined in [incident 35.](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/incidents/35) ','2024-05-31 10:53:42','Competitors claimed they got misscrambles after round','2025-05-15 06:50:34'),
(106,'2024-05-02 01:13:35',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'After the competition had ended, delegates noticed that one of the cubes used by a competitor in Multiblind had a centerpiece that was texturally affected. The delegates noted that it was possible to distinguish the center from other centers by touch. The decision was to count the puzzle as unsolved for the attempts per [3k2b](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3k2b). That is, the number of solved puzzles for the two attempts both decreased by 1. Even though we cannot confirm whether or not the cube was actually solved at the end of the attempt, submitting a legal cube is the responsibility of the competitor and it would be unfair to count the puzzle as solved. Additionally, it is more likely that the cube was solved than unsolved. ','2024-05-31 11:19:39','Cube was found to have textured center for multiblind attempt at the end of competition','2024-05-31 11:19:39'),
(107,'2024-05-02 01:24:53',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'Towards the end of a solve, when the competitor went to stop the timer, they bumped it with the puzzle and the timer fell into their lap before stopping the timer. The delegates awarded a *provisional* extra, but kept the original result. \r\n\r\nThe decision was made to keep the original result (not use the provisional), as it was deemed that it was the competitor\'s fault for knocking over the timer. ','2024-05-31 10:54:50','Competitor knocked timer into lap','2024-05-31 10:54:50'),
(108,'2024-05-16 02:38:08',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'Towards the end of a competitor\'s multi-blind attempt, the judge went to go stop the stopwatch. After the attempt finished, the judge proceeded to check and count the cubes. They then went to reference the time on the stopwatch, but found that the timer had been reset (likely accidentally) to 0:00.00. The judge and competitor both seemed to remember the exact same time that was shown on the stopwatch prior to the accidental reset. \r\n\r\nThe decision was made to use the time that was shared in memory by the competitor and the judge since the competitor did not cause the reset and since the time remembered was the same by both the competitor and the judge. \r\n\r\nWhile seemingly a malfunction of the stopwatch in this case, it serves as a reminder that timers should not be reset before the result is written down and signed for. If a competitor resets their timer before the time is fully written down, then it must be recorded as DNF (See [Regulation A6f1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A6f1)).','2024-05-31 10:59:21','Stopwatch reset after stopping multi-blind attempt','2024-05-31 10:59:21'),
(109,'2024-05-16 02:45:34',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A competitor flipped over the scramble sheet for an FMC attempt before the attempt started. The delegates assure that they had made it clear not to flip over the paper prior to the attempt. Since the competitor saw the scramble due to their own flaw, it was decided to rule this attempt as a DNF.','2024-05-31 11:00:10','Competitor flipped over FMC scramble before attempt began','2024-05-31 11:00:10'),
(110,'2024-05-16 03:00:02',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'A few days after a competiton, a competitor contacted a delegate asking if one of the cubes they used at the competition (which was also a cube they used to set a record) was a legal puzzle. \r\n\r\nThe competitor claimed that the puzzle made different sounds depending on the location of a certain corner piece. They also mentioned that one center cap had a slighly different texture than the others (thus making it potentially invalid for blind solving, which is where the record was set).\r\n\r\nThe decision was made to keep the result. The following criteria were used in making the decision:\r\n1. The sound difference was negligible and would require an entirely silent environment for it to be potentially noticeable (which is unlikely the case in 3x3 blindfolded).\r\n2. The sound difference was only noticed after the competition, and video evidence showed that no advantage was gained.\r\n3. The delegates had ruled during the competition that the texture difference was reasonable. \r\n\r\nAs per [Regulation 3j1](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#3j1), puzzles are allowed to have reasonable wear. Competitors are encouraged to bring any concerns to their local delegates regarding the legality of their puzzles. The [visual guide](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1m6THsA8fXRN7QFM4ApJbm6eVODKGbMLx/view) in [Guideline 3j++](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/guidelines.html#3j++) is also a good reference for competitors. ','2024-05-31 11:04:17','Competitor asked about potentially illegal cube days after competition','2024-05-31 11:04:17'),
(111,'2024-05-27 01:54:57',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'DISCLAIMER: Please note that as of 2025, [A2e2](https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/regulations/#A2e2) explicitly prohibits the competitor from lifting the cover with associated DNF penalty.\r\n\r\nA competitor posted one of their solves from a competition online, and it was seen that the competitor had lifted their own cube cover (as opposed to the judge doing so). The video indicated the competitor signaling they were \"ready\" to the judge and the judge starting the stopwatch without lifting the cube cover. The competitor then proceeded to lift the cover for themselves.\r\n\r\nThough the actions seem in violation with regulation A3b2, this regulation does not have an associated penalty. Additionally, the incident was only discovered after the competition, making the opportunity for an extra attempt unavailable. \r\n\r\nThe WRC decided to keep the attempt as is with no penalty, because it was deemed that it was the judge\'s mistake that caused the incident, the competitor gained no advantage, and that the stopwatch was started before the cover was lifted.\r\n\r\nAll competitors should take note that if a similar incident were to occur to them, they should immediately call a Delegate to rectify the incident on the spot. \r\n\r\n','2024-05-31 11:06:11','Competitor uncovered puzzle after judge had started the timer','2025-06-01 21:25:57');
